{{Hiero | Retjenu<ref>Faulkner, Ramond O. ''Middle Egyptian.'' p. 154. Griffith Institute, Oxford, 1962.</ref><br>(''[[determinative|determ.]]''-[[hill-country (hieroglyph)|foreign land]]) | <hiero>r:T-n:nw-w-N25</hiero> | align=right | era=default}}

'''Retjenu''' (''rṯnw; Reṯenu, Retenu''), was an [[Ancient Egypt]]ian name for [[Canaan]] and [[History of Syria#Syria in Antiquity|Syria]]. It covered the region from the Negev Desert north to the [[Orontes River]]. The borders of Retjenu shifted with time, but it generally consisted of three regions. The southernmost was [[Djahy]], which had about the same boundaries as [[Canaan]].<ref name="Boundaries">Steindorff, George. ''When Egypt Ruled the East.'' p. 47. University of Chicago Press, 1942.</ref> [[History of ancient Lebanon|Lebanon]] proper was located in the middle, between the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] and the [[Orontes River]].<ref name="Boundaries"/> North of Lebanon was designated [[Amorite|Amurru]], the land of the Amorites.<ref name="Boundaries"/>

The earliest attestation of the name occurs in the ''[[Tale of Sinuhe]],'' inscribed on a [[Ostracon|piece of limestone]] in 14th century BC.

